---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { site, withBase } from '@config/site';
---

<BaseLayout title={`Insights — ${site.name}`} description="Practical notes on recurring customer questions, purchase friction and feature requests as operating evidence." path="/insights">
  <section class="page-hero insight-hero"><div class="wrap page-hero__grid"><div class="reveal is-visible"><span class="eyebrow">Insights</span><h1>Small operating problems, examined properly.</h1></div><p class="page-hero__copy reveal is-visible">These are not predictions or generic leadership lessons. Each note takes one pattern, shows what evidence matters and ends with a practical decision.</p></div></section>
  <section class="section zone-paper"><div class="wrap insight-list">
    <article class="insight reveal" id="repeated-questions"><div class="insight__meta"><span>Support operations</span><small>6 minute read</small></div><div class="insight__body"><h2>A repeated customer question is often a design failure with a support cost.</h2><p>The first time a customer asks a question, it may be a customer question. The hundredth time, it is evidence that the business keeps creating the same uncertainty.</p><p>The mistake is to solve only the conversation. A faster reply improves one case; it does not reduce the reason customers need to ask. I would group the contacts by journey stage, compare the promise with the information available at that moment, and trace who owns the missing answer.</p><div class="insight__decision"><strong>Useful test</strong><p>If the team answered this question perfectly every time, would customers still need to ask it? If yes, the next improvement belongs upstream.</p></div><p>The intervention may be a clearer sentence, a status update, better onboarding, a policy change or a new workflow. Support capacity is one option, not the automatic answer.</p></div></article>
    <article class="insight reveal" id="more-traffic"><div class="insight__meta"><span>Customer-led growth</span><small>5 minute read</small></div><div class="insight__body"><h2>More traffic is expensive evidence that the buying journey is still broken.</h2><p>When sales slow down, increasing media spend feels active. But traffic does not repair an unclear offer, missing trust, a difficult checkout or order operations that cannot keep the promise.</p><p>Before scaling acquisition, I would compare the ad promise with the landing page, identify the decisions customers must make, review the information available at each hesitation point and check what happens after the order is placed.</p><div class="insight__decision"><strong>Useful test</strong><p>Can a high-intent customer understand the difference, trust the promise and complete the purchase without asking the business to explain the page?</p></div><p>If the answer is no, the first growth investment should improve the value of the traffic the business already has.</p></div></article>
    <article class="insight reveal" id="feature-request"><div class="insight__meta"><span>Product requirements</span><small>5 minute read</small></div><div class="insight__body"><h2>A feature request describes the customer's preferred answer—not always the real problem.</h2><p>“Add a chatbot” may mean customers cannot find an answer. “Build a dashboard” may mean managers do not trust the current status. “Add another field” may mean the handoff lacks one piece of information.</p><p>Before writing a requirement, I would restate the user need without naming the requested feature, map when the need appears, check how often it happens and test whether process, content or ownership could remove it more simply.</p><div class="insight__decision"><strong>Useful test</strong><p>If the requested feature disappeared from the conversation, what outcome would the user still need?</p></div><p>That answer is the requirement. The feature is only one possible implementation.</p></div></article>
  </div></section>
  <section class="section insight-cta"><div class="wrap insight-cta__inner reveal"><div><span class="eyebrow">Apply the thinking</span><h2>See how these decisions appear inside real work.</h2></div><a class="btn btn--primary" href={withBase('/work')}>View selected work</a></div></section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .insight-hero{background:radial-gradient(circle at 82% 28%,rgba(187,165,255,.14),transparent 25rem),var(--night)}.insight-list{display:flex;flex-direction:column}.insight{display:grid;grid-template-columns:220px minmax(0,1fr);gap:clamp(2rem,8vw,7rem);padding:4rem 0;border-bottom:1px solid var(--paper-line)}.insight:first-child{padding-top:0}.insight__meta{display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:.5rem}.insight__meta span{color:var(--signal-deep);font:850 .65rem var(--font-head);letter-spacing:.12em;text-transform:uppercase}.insight__meta small{color:var(--slate-soft)}.insight__body{max-width:760px}.insight h2{margin-bottom:1.4rem;font-size:clamp(2rem,3.5vw,3.4rem)}.insight p{margin-bottom:1rem;color:var(--ink-soft)}.insight__decision{margin:1.8rem 0;padding:1.5rem;border-radius:var(--shape-md);background:var(--signal-soft)}.insight__decision strong{color:var(--signal-deep);font:850 .65rem var(--font-head);letter-spacing:.1em;text-transform:uppercase}.insight__decision p{margin:.65rem 0 0;color:var(--ink);font-weight:600}.insight-cta{background:var(--night)}.insight-cta__inner{display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr auto;gap:2rem;align-items:center}.insight-cta h2{max-width:760px;margin-top:.8rem;font-size:var(--fs-h2)}
  @media(max-width:760px){.insight{grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.2rem}.insight__meta{flex-direction:row;justify-content:space-between}.insight-cta__inner{grid-template-columns:1fr}}
</style>
